node.title: 'A true national effort': PM hails 80pc national vaccine milestone, but some states still lagging behind
node.alt: A person gets a vaccination in their right arm by a nurse.
node.description: Eighty per cent of eligible Australians aged 16 and over have now received two doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, Scott Morrison says.
node.content:
["Eighty per cent of eligible Australians aged 16 and over have now received two doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, marking a major milestone set by the federal government at the beginning of the inoculation campaign.", "But little will change as a result of reaching the national target, with states and territories having set their own pathways out of restrictions.", "Prime Minister Scott Morrison celebrated reaching the 80 per cent vaccination target, describing it as a \"magnificent milestone\" in a social media video.", "\"That's four out of five, how good is that? This has been a true Australian national effort,\" he said.", "\"A big thanks goes to our nurses, our doctors, our healthcare workers and pharmacists, everyone who has been involved in this extraordinary effort.\"", "But the nationwide figure belies the uneven inoculation levels around the country.", "Vaccination rates are highest in the ACT, where close to 95 per cent of the population aged 16 years and over is fully vaccinated.", "New South Wales is not far behind, with 90 per cent of the eligible population having had both doses of the vaccine.", "But in the Northern Territory and Western Australia, only 65 per cent are fully vaccinated. In Queensland the figure is 66 per cent, and in\u00a0South Australia 69 per cent.", "While New South Wales, Victoria and the ACT are opening up interstate borders and beginning to allow international arrivals, West Australians will have to wait until late January or early February for their restrictions to ease.", "", "
Scott Morrison has urged unvaccinated Australians to make a booking as soon as possible.\u00a0(ABC News: Matt Roberts)
", "Mr Morrison was optimistic about the progress in Western Australia and Queensland, noting those states will \"will join the 80 per cent first-dose club in the coming days.\"", "But federal, state and territory leaders expressed concerns yesterday at a National Cabinet meeting about the risk of COVID-19 outbreaks in Indigenous communities as restrictions ease.", "All jurisdictions will be updating their plans on how to manage outbreaks over the next month, particularly for regional and remote communities where vaccination levels are lower.", "The updates will include plans for quicker responses when more vaccines or quarantine facilities are needed.", "Local Indigenous community groups and emergency services will be consulted as part of the updates.", "Mr Morrison thanked Australians for getting vaccinated and urged anyone who is yet to be vaccinated to make a booking straight away.", "\"Please, book it in now. We want you to be part of this, too.\"", "\"It isn't over yet (but) we're on our way back. Planes are back in the air, the kids are back at school, the restaurants are opening and a big Christmas is coming for all of us.\""]
